<JournalEntry
  title="D442 Digital Clinical Experience Orientation – Part 1 of 5"
  date="2026-03-25"
  entryType="Digital Clinical Experience"
  course="D442 – Basic Nursing Skills"
>
  <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
    Today I began the <strong>Digital Clinical Experience (DCE) Orientation</strong> for
    <strong>D442 Basic Nursing Skills</strong> — Part 1 of 5. This first session focuses on
    getting acquainted with the DCE platform and practising the structured patient-interaction
    scripts required for each encounter. All patient interactions follow a standard sequence:
    always <strong>Greet first</strong>, then move to assessment, education, and empathy as
    appropriate.
  </p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin:1.5rem 0 0.75rem;">
    🗣️ Stock Patient-Interaction Responses — Patient: Tina
  </h2>

  <p style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
    The following are the stock responses to use during interactions with patient
    <strong>Tina</strong>. These are memorised phrases that align with the DCE scoring rubric
    and should be delivered verbatim (or very close to verbatim) in the correct order.
  </p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:0.9rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background:#eef2ff; color:#3730a3;">
        <th style="text-align:left; padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #c7d2fe; width:22%;">Action</th>
        <th style="text-align:left; padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #c7d2fe;">Statement</th>
        <th style="text-align:center; padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #c7d2fe; width:14%;">Order</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="background:#f0fdf4;">
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; font-weight:700; color:#166534;">Greet</td>
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; color:#1e293b;">
          "Hello. My name is Scott, and I'm here to interview and examine you."
        </td>
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; text-align:center; font-weight:700; color:#166534;">1st — Always</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; font-weight:700; color:#0369a1;">Educate</td>
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; color:#1e293b;">
          "Treating high cholesterol helps lower your risk of stroke."
        </td>
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; text-align:center;">—</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background:#fefce8;">
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; font-weight:700; color:#92400e;">Empathize</td>
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; color:#1e293b;">
          "It sounds like that was a challenging time for you."
        </td>
        <td style="padding:0.5rem 0.75rem; border:1px solid #d1d5db; text-align:center;">—</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div style="background:#f0fdf4; border:1px solid #bbf7d0; border-radius:0.6rem; padding:0.9rem 1.1rem; font-size:0.875rem; color:#166534; margin-bottom:1.5rem; display:flex; align-items:flex-start; gap:0.6rem;">
    <span style="flex-shrink:0; font-size:1rem;">✅</span>
    <span>
      <strong>Key rule:</strong> The <em>Greet</em> statement must always be delivered
      <strong>first</strong> in every patient encounter, before any assessment, education,
      or empathy statements.
    </span>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin:1.5rem 0 0.75rem;">
    📋 Patient Communication Standards
  </h2>

  <p style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
    All verbal communication with patients during DCE encounters must follow these standards:
  </p>

  <ul style="margin-bottom:1.25rem; padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:1.9; color:#334155;">
    <li>
      <strong>Use correct spelling and grammar.</strong> Written notes and spoken scripts must be
      grammatically correct and free of spelling errors.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Make questions specific.</strong> Ask about one precise topic at a time so the
      patient can give a clear, focused answer.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Avoid pronouns</strong> such as <em>he, they, her, it, that,</em> and <em>this.</em>
      Use the patient's name or a specific noun instead to prevent ambiguity.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Avoid compound questions</strong> that use <em>"or"</em> or <em>"and."</em>
      Break multi-part questions into separate, single-focus questions.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Avoid sentence fragments.</strong> Every statement and question must be a complete
      sentence with a subject and a verb so the meaning is unambiguous and professional.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ask about one subject at a time.</strong> Focus each question on a single topic
      or body system. Move to the next subject only after the patient has fully responded to
      the current question.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>If the patient is unable to answer, try a broader question.</strong> When a
      specific question produces no response or causes confusion, step back and ask a more
      open-ended question about the same subject to give the patient an easier entry point.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Avoid medical jargon.</strong> Substitute plain, everyday language whenever possible
      so the patient understands without needing clinical training. For example, say
      <em>"high blood pressure"</em> instead of <em>"hypertension,"</em> or
      <em>"trouble breathing"</em> instead of <em>"dyspnea."</em>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Provide clear context for questions.</strong> Before asking a question, briefly
      explain why the information is needed so the patient understands the relevance and is
      more likely to give a complete, accurate answer.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <div style="background:#fefce8; border:1px solid #fde68a; border-radius:0.6rem; padding:0.9rem 1.1rem; font-size:0.875rem; color:#92400e; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
    <strong>Examples of common pitfalls to avoid:</strong>
    <ul style="margin:0.5rem 0 0; padding-left:1.25rem; line-height:1.8;">
      <li>
        ✗ <em>"Do you feel <u>that</u> the pain is getting better or worse?"</em> — pronoun "that" + compound "or"
      </li>
      <li>
        ✓ <em>"On a scale of 0 to 10, how would Tina rate the pain right now?"</em> — specific, single-focus, pronoun-free
      </li>
      <li>
        ✗ <em>"Has <u>she</u> been taking <u>it</u> every day <u>and</u> eating well?"</em> — pronouns + compound "and"
      </li>
      <li>
        ✓ <em>"Has Tina been taking the prescribed medication every day?"</em> — specific noun, one question
      </li>
      <li>
        ✗ <em>"Are you experiencing any dyspnea or diaphoresis?"</em> — medical jargon + compound "or"
      </li>
      <li>
        ✓ <em>"Is Tina having any trouble breathing?"</em> — plain language, single-focus
      </li>
      <li>
        ✗ <em>"What is your pain level?"</em> — no context; patient may not know why the question matters
      </li>
      <li>
        ✓ <em>"To help manage Tina's comfort, I need to understand the pain level. On a scale of 0 to 10, what number best describes the pain right now?"</em> — context provided, plain language, specific
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p style="margin-bottom:1rem; color:#475569; font-size:0.9rem;">
    <em>Additional interaction scripts and clinical skills content will be added as the
    remaining DCE orientation parts (Parts 2–5) are completed.</em>
  </p>
</JournalEntry>
